Clearly, there is a class bias, a condition observed when the proportion of events is much smaller than proportion of non-events. There are many ways to deal with class imbalance but will build model as is.

The above correlation plot shows that there is a significant correlation between variables OldBalanceOrig and NewBalanceOrig; OldBalanceDest and NewBalanceDest; and Type_CASH_OUT and Type_TRANSFER. We can make use of Variance Inflation Factor to assess whether these correlations are statistically significant or not.

#Binomial regression
full <- glm(isFraud ~ ., data=final.rawdata, family = "binomial")
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred

The summary of the model shows all the features in the model are significant to the model.

Type_TRANSFER variable was not defined because of singularity means that the variable is not linearly independent. This is because the information given by this variable is already contained in the other variable, and thus redundant.

Even if we remove the Type_TRANSFER variable from the above model, will obtain the same result for the rest of the variables.

full1 <- glm(isFraud ~ .-Type_TRANSFER, data=final.rawdata, family = "binomial")

#Detect Multicollinearity
car::vif(full1)
##            Amt OldBalanceOrig NewBalanceOrig OldBalanceDest NewBalanceDest 
##     143.591567     184.649435      13.190697       9.882184      12.502865 
##  Type_CASH_OUT           hour 
##       1.048996       1.009511

As noted in the above correlation matrix/plot that there was significant correlation among few variables. Now the above VIF confirmed the evidence of multicollinearity in the model.

Since the VIF shows presence of multicollinearity in the model, the estimates developed on this model would be unstable.

One way to overcome this issue is to drop the other variables because both variables are bringing same information to the model so there is no point in keeping both of them.

#dropping one of the correlated variables
final.rawdata.multc <- final.rawdata %>% select(-c('NewBalanceOrig', 'NewBalanceDest','Type_TRANSFER'))
str(final.rawdata.multc)

Interpretation of the model:

Each regression coefficient in the model is statistically significant.

Now can see that the log(odds) of isFraud are increased by a factor of increase in Amt (holding other input variables constant).

The log(odds) of isFraud increase with Amt and OldBalanceOrig and decrease with OldBalanceDest, Type_CASH_OUT and hour.

In other words, the more the amount in old balance orig the more the chance of occurring fraud. And the lesser the old balance dest, the more the chance of occurring fraud.

For Type_Cash_Out feature, the lesser the customer uses cash_out type transaction, the more the chance of occurring fraud.

For hour feature, as the hours gets decreased from 24 hrs to 0 hrs, there is high chance of occurring fraud. Further this was noted in the earlier EDA that fraud transactions took place throughout the clock.

There is an error message which was due to biases in estimates of population parameter. Firths method can be helpful when fitting logistic regression models to data containing complete/quasi-separation or high bias.

#Goodness-of-fit test Another approach to determine whether or not the above model is statistically fit is through goodness-of-fit test. The interpretation of the confusion matrix is that there were about 321391 records belonged to legitimate class and the model also predicted them as non-fraudulent records which is correct prediction for class 0.

For fraudulent records, about 111 records belonged to and the model also predicted 155 records belonged to fraud cases which is also correct classification for 1 class.

In actual there were 40 records which were belonged to non-fraudulent records but the model predicted these 40 records as fraudulent records which is incorrect prediction by the model for class 0. And 694 records were actually belonged to fraud records, but the model predicted these 694 records as non-fraudulent records which is incorrect prediction for class 1.

In terms of overall accuracy, the above model has done pretty well with 99.8% which is good.

One thing we need to notice very closely in the above confusion matrix is that the model predicted legitimate records more accurately which is almost 100% than fraudulent records which is just 13.8%. In other words, the model has done pretty well in predicting non-fraudulent cases, but failed in more accurately predicting fraudulent transactions.

This is because of class imbalance in the data. As we have seen above that the dataset has higher number of records for legitimate records with 321431 in comparison to fraudulent records which are only 805. Hence the non-fraudlent records being the higher class in the given dataset is dominating the whole show in this prediction model. In such scenario, we cannot build model based on accuracy metric.

As our primary area of focus in building the above model is to predict fraudulent cases more accurately than non-fraudulent cases, then sensitivity and specificity comes into picture.

One way to overcome this issue is through ROC curve.

#Accuracy plot

library(ROCR)
## Loading required package: gplots
## 
## Attaching package: 'gplots'
## The following object is masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     lowess
pred <- prediction(pred_prob, train$isFraud)
eval <- performance(pred, "acc")
plot(eval)

The plot shows cutoff values from 0 to 1 and for different cut-off values, what is the accuracy the model achieves. This accuracy is overall accuracy in the model.

We can see in the plot that when the cutoff value is approximately 0.01 the accuracy is almost 100%. In the model, the accuracy seems to be constant throughout with different cutoff values which is because of class imbalance.

#ROC Curve
library(ROCR)
pred <- prediction(pred_prob, train$isFraud)
perf <- performance(pred, "tpr","fpr")

#ROC plot
plot(perf, colorize=TRUE, print.cutoffs.at=seq(0,1,0.001))
abline(a=0,b=1)

ROC plot shows how the model is performing against the benchmark.

Now we can see some improvement in sensitivity with 21.9% as it was earlier at 13.8%.

The overall accuracy in the model with 0.1 threshold is at 99.7%.
